cs.LG, cs.DS, cs.NA, cs.CG, cs.CV

The paper discusses a variant of the Frank-Wolfe method for training large-scale non-linear Support Vector Machines (SVMs), which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG). The method is based on a concave maximization problem on the simplex, which is related to computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also presents experiments on classification datasets, which involves computer vision (cs.CV). The analysis of the algorithm's convergence rate and number of iterations involves numerical analysis (cs.NA). Finally, the use of sparsity in the SVM model may also relate to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS).
